{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17491527","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17491527"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T05:51:09+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T05:51:09+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"970"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"970","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/970"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.06,0.69,0.08,0.13,0.04]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"970"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"103849"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"970","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/970"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"970"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"86274"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"14"},{"type":"tags","id":"23"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"1051"},{"type":"tags","id":"1052"},{"type":"tags","id":"1061"},{"type":"tags","id":"1984"},{"type":"tags","id":"4466"},{"type":"tags","id":"4467"},{"type":"tags","id":"5771"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"11837"},{"type":"contributions","id":"13067"},{"type":"contributions","id":"13304"},{"type":"contributions","id":"35930"},{"type":"contributions","id":"36815"},{"type":"contributions","id":"37052"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"103849","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/103849"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 27-year-old woman is being reviewed on a home visit seven days after an uncomplicated vaginal delivery of her healthy girl. She has been well until yesterday when she developed fever with rigors, associated with nausea and vomiting. She has no significant medical history, no known allergies, and takes no regular medications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears unwell. Her pulse rate is 90/min, blood pressure 120/70 mmHg, respiratory rate 20/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 38.5\u00b0C. Her uterus is palpable and tender on abdominal examination. She is transferred to hospital where a high vaginal swab is collected.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate immediate management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["IV amoxicillin and clavulanate","IV gentamicin, amoxicillin and metronidazole","Dilation and curettage","IV gentamicin, cefazolin and metronidazole","IV trimethoprim, sulfamethoxazole and metronidazole"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with severe postpartum endometritis, characterised by fever, rigors, nausea, vomiting and uterine tenderness seven days after delivery. The presence of systemic features indicates severe disease requiring immediate intravenous antibiotic therapy. The standard three-drug regimen for severe postpartum endometritis is \u003Cstrong\u003Egentamicin, amoxicillin and metronidazole\u003C/strong\u003E, which provides broad-spectrum coverage against the typical causative organisms including \u003Cem\u003EStreptococcus pyogenes\u003C/em\u003E, \u003Cem\u003EEscherichia coli\u003C/em\u003E, and anaerobes.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIntravenous amoxicillin and clavulanate\u003C/strong\u003E would be appropriate for nonsevere postpartum endometritis where the infection is localised without fever or systemic features. However, this patient has clear systemic symptoms requiring the more intensive three-drug regimen.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDilation and curettage\u003C/strong\u003E carries an increased risk of uterine perforation in the setting of acute infection and should not be performed before appropriate antibiotic therapy has been initiated and the patient has clinically improved.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EGentamicin, cefazolin and metronidazole\u003C/strong\u003E is an alternative three-drug regimen used for patients who have had nonsevere hypersensitivity reactions to penicillins. Since this patient has no known allergies, the standard amoxicillin-containing regimen is preferred.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETrimethoprim, sulfamethoxazole and metronidazole\u003C/strong\u003E would be used for nonsevere endometritis in patients with penicillin hypersensitivity, but this patient has severe disease requiring intravenous therapy and has no documented allergies.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EEarly recognition and treatment within one hour is essential as puerperal sepsis remains an important cause of maternal mortality. Blood cultures should be collected but should not delay antibiotic administration.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Severe postpartum endometritis with systemic features requires immediate broad-spectrum intravenous antibiotics to prevent progression to sepsis.","The standard three-drug regimen for severe postpartum endometritis is gentamicin, amoxicillin and metronidazole.","Blood cultures should be collected but should not delay antibiotic administration in severe endometritis."],"references":["Identification and management of maternal sepsis during and following pregnancy (Green-top Guideline No. 64) [online]. 2024. Available at: https://www.rcog.org.uk/guidance/browse-all-guidance/green-top-guidelines/identification-and-management-of-maternal-sepsis-during-and-following-pregnancy-green-top-guideline-no-64/","French LM, Smaill FM. Antibiotic regimens for endometritis after delivery. Cochrane Database Syst Rev. 2004 Oct 18;(4):CD001067. doi: 10.1002/14651858.CD001067.pub2. Update in: Cochrane Database Syst Rev. 2015;2:CD001067. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/15495005/","Mackeen AD, Packard RE, Ota E, Speer L. Antibiotic regimens for postpartum endometritis. Cochrane Database Syst Rev. 2015 Feb 2;2015(2):CD001067. doi: 10.1002/14651858.CD001067.pub3. PMID: 25922861; PMCID: PMC7050613. Available from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/25922861/","Taylor M, Jenkins SM, Pillarisetty LS. Endometritis. [Updated 2023 Oct 26]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2025 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK553124/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"86274"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"970"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"86274","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/86274"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-05-27T17:46:50+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-05-27T17:47:43+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"970"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"103849"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"14","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/14"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udda0","name":"Infectious Diseases","synonyms":["ID"],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2021-05-21T07:51:58+09:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"23","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/23"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udd30","name":"Obstetrics","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"3"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"24","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tag